Midgaard's sealed warrant archive from the Ash-and-Iron period is held in the Violet Compact's deep registry — the same administrative system that processed the warrants retains custody of them.
The archive contains three types of records: the original warrant issuances (identifying subject, issuing magistrate, and stated grounds), the Violet Compact's reclassification documents (converting civic identity to "arcane material" designation), and the transfer manifests (recording subjects moved to Conclave custody along with payment received).
The transfer manifests are the most politically significant: they document payment received, making the transaction financially traceable rather than merely administratively recorded.
The Continuity faction's legal argument for keeping the warrants sealed is procedural: sealed warrants from emergency charter law remain sealed until a formal unsealing proceeding is completed, and completing the unsealing proceeding would require convening a tribunal that has authority over documents from a governance period whose institutions no longer exist.
The Reckoning faction's counter-argument is that the procedural requirement for unsealing is itself a product of the same governance period that issued the warrants — citing the procedure to protect the warrant contents is circular.
Charter Sovereignty office maintains that the unsealing question is a matter of constitutional law rather than political will; the Continuity faction uses this framing; the Reckoning faction calls it a deliberate deferral.
The Temple of the Resounding Heart holds memorial rolls from the Ash-and-Iron period that cross-reference names with dates of disappearance; some of those names correspond to warrant subjects, providing an unofficial parallel record.

