Kowloon's sealed records from the Ash-and-Iron period parallel Midgaard's sealed warrants from the delta settlements' end of the same apparatus.
The Black Ledger's population lists correspond to the same transfer chain: where Midgaard's warrants name subjects being transferred out, Kowloon's Black Ledger names subjects whose registry entries were stripped before transfer.
The institutional guilt is mutual and parallel, which creates the dynamic Kowloon's Continuity faction relies on: opening either city's records creates pressure to open the other's, and no city's Continuity faction wants to be the first to open.
Kowloon's Neon Covenant was partly designed to prevent sealed warrants from being possible within the city's governance structure: the jade seal's two-magistrate requirement applies specifically to any proclamation that removes a person from the civic registry.
The two-magistrate requirement means that no single official can issue a Kowloon-equivalent sealed warrant unilaterally — the structural prevention of the single-magistrate emergency warrant that Midgaard used during the Ash-and-Iron period.
The Courier Lantern Office's color-coded registry system was designed so that all registered persons are visible in the civic record regardless of their status — there is no "arcane material" reclassification mechanism in Kowloon's system because the Neon Covenant's founding design specifically excluded it.

