Kiess's founding charter clause prohibiting sealed warrants is the most specific piece of anti-warrant law in the five-city network.
The clause states: "No sealed warrant issued by a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen; no warrant issued within Kiess jurisdiction shall be sealed against the named party's knowledge; and no warrant shall convert a named party from civic to material classification."
The three-part structure was written to close each of the Ash-and-Iron warrant mechanism's three components: the retroactive sealing of predecessor warrants, the denial of knowledge to warrant subjects, and the reclassification from civic person to arcane material.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's triune seal is Kiess's physical proof that the warrant apparatus and the Conclave were connected: the disc was recovered from Evermeet's ruins at a location that the Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains document as a transfer point.
Kiess's formal repudiation of sealed-warrant governance creates an asymmetry with Midgaard that makes inter-city archive discussion structurally difficult: Kiess has already admitted institutional guilt and repudiated the practice, while Midgaard has done neither.
The asymmetry means that any five-city commission convened to address sealed warrant history would include one city that has formally repudiated the practice, creating implicit pressure on cities that have not.

