Rakuen's founding population included people who arrived carrying sealed-warrant classifications from Midgaard's intake system.
The Garden Ledger's founding-generation records show dual-registry entries — Midgaard intake numbers alongside Rakuen registration numbers — that correspond to people processed through the emergency warrant system before being routed south.
Some of these dual-registry entries correspond to the same warrant subjects named in the sealed warrant archive, cross-referenced through Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains that documented proceedings before the warrants were sealed.
Rakuen's political class has debated whether to formally petition for access to the sealed warrants that correspond to Garden Ledger founding-generation entries.
The petition would be procedurally novel: Rakuen would be requesting access to Midgaard's sealed records on behalf of people who are part of Rakuen's own founding population.
The Compact Purist faction opposes the petition: seeking access to Midgaard's warrants acknowledges Midgaard's jurisdictional authority over Rakuen's founding population history.
The Assimilation League faction supports the petition: Midgaard's institutional records are where the documentation is, and refusing to access them because of jurisdictional objections means accepting the sealed warrant's denial of history as a practical outcome.

