Mafdet's maritime legal tradition has no internal mechanism equivalent to sealed warrants — maritime law's oath attestation system cannot be sealed against the named party's knowledge without invalidating the oath.
An oath witnessed by a party who does not know they are being attested is void under maritime law; the sealed warrant's fundamental structure (the named party does not know) is therefore legally impossible under Mafdet's legal tradition.
The Strandline Compact's founding document includes a clause rejecting any warrant that "removes a party from the register of their own knowledge" — a maritime law formulation of the same anti-sealed-warrant principle that Kiess's charter states in charter-law terms.
Mafdet's formal distance from the sealed warrant tradition is the basis for the Swift Court's role as a neutral forum in cargo disputes where one party is from a sealed-warrant governance tradition: the Swift Court's oaths are incapable of incorporating a sealed component.
The mercy-freight classification Mafdet extended to Rakuen during the Ash-and-Iron years was partly a practical response to the sealed warrant mechanism: Mafdet could provide supply access that did not require Rakuen's population to interface with Midgaard's warrant-bearing intake system.

