---
Ashborn are the population most directly harmed by Midgaard's sealed warrants from the Ash-and-Iron period.
The misclassification of Ashborn as a human subtype made them subject to human-debtor warrants — the same warrants that authorized condemned-debtor transfers to the Spirebound Conclave.
Ashborn oral tradition preserves accounts of individuals who arrived at Midgaard's intake yards, were registered under emergency warrants, and did not return.
The Conclave's Ember Canon program — which theorized that fire was the most fundamental transformative force — was motivated in part by observing early Ashborn and attempting to replicate volcanic transformation through fire ritual. The program obtained experimental subjects partly through Midgaard's warrant system.
Ashborn communities' demand for the sealed warrants to be opened is therefore simultaneously a demand for historical acknowledgment and a demand for the experimental record of what was done to their ancestors.
The Reckoning faction's alliance with Ashborn community advocates is the most emotionally direct cross-group alignment in Midgaard's current political landscape: both want the warrants opened, for reasons that are simultaneously political (accountability) and personal (documentation of family loss).
The Continuity faction's procedural argument — that opening warrants requires a tribunal with authority over a dissolved governance period — does not address Ashborn communities' position that the dissolved governance period is precisely what must be examined.
No Continuity faction official has publicly acknowledged the Ember Canon's use of Ashborn subjects; the connection is documented in Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains but not in any officially recognized archive.

