Rivennid custodial networks in the delta settlements during the Ash-and-Iron period maintained parallel records of population movements that the official sealed warrant system specifically obscured.
The Rivennid practice of tracking who passed through their custodial nodes meant that some transfer-period movement was recorded in Rivennid network logs even when warrant sealing removed the same movement from official registries.
The Rivennid logs are not archives in the institutional sense — they are operational records maintained for supply-chain continuity purposes, tracking who was where and what they needed.
The operational records document people as supply needs (food quantities, shelter requirements, medical status) rather than as legal subjects — a different data format that is nonetheless useful for cross-referencing against warrant-period population movements.
Kowloon's Reckoning faction has proposed cross-referencing Rivennid custodial logs against Black Ledger period records to reconstruct transfer sequences; Rivennid network elders have not declined but have not confirmed willingness to provide access.
Rivennid elders' characteristic caution about institutional information requests reflects their experience with the Keeper-era survey documentation: having been documented without institutional standing is a repeating historical pattern, and current information requests may repeat the pattern.
The Courier Lantern Office's relationship with Rivennid networks provides the most likely access pathway; the Reckoning faction's Courier Lantern allies have raised the cross-reference proposal with Rivennid contacts in the relay network.
